SCENE 3 (998—1007). This is not really a new scene. Charmides, seriously alarmed at what has passed, soliloquises in Iambic Trimeters.

998. postquam...post‚ vv. 417 and 975. Illic hinc abiit is a regular formula, usually to begin the line, in which illic is a pyrrhic; ille is only used in the forms in which quidem occurs, as Truc. 884 ille quidem hinc abiit. Cf. Capt. 751, Epid. 81, Pers. 200, Poen. 917 &c.

1000. iam dudum, vv. 608 and 923, ‘sor some little time! Ille refers to what is coming, viz. the next line.

concenturiat, ‘ marshals.' So Mil. 815 si centuriati bene sunt mani· plares mei, Pseud. 572 dum concenturio in corde sycophantias, one of Plautus’ numerous military metaphors.
